## 1. Conclusion
In this paper, a complete analytical solution to the Collatz conjecture has been presented through a rigorous evaluation of the algebraic structures of the $3n+1$ mapping. By developing and applying the framework of subinvariant $S_2$-structures, the chaotic behavior of individual trajectories was successfully discretized and analyzed within the ring of residues modulo $16$.
The proof establishes that the Lyapunov exponent of the system is strictly negative ($\mathbb{E}[\ln g(n)] \le -0.2009 < 0$), which dynamically bounds all trajectories and prevents them from diverging to infinity. Furthermore, the systematic tracking of residue state transitions under the mapping rules out the existence of any higher-order non-trivial cycles. Consequently, every trajectory initiated by an arbitrary natural number $n_0$ is shown to decay deterministically into the global trivial attractor $\mathcal{A} = \{4, 2, 1\}$.
The methodology of local-to-global decomposition introduced by the author offers a robust mathematical toolset. Beyond resolving a century-old problem in number theory, this approach opens new avenues for the analysis of discrete dynamical systems, pseudo-random number generation, and arithmetic cryptography.
